{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491445"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:47:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:47:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"941"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/941"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.11,0.39,0.15,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"941"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110361"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/941"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"941"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92634"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"581"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"305"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31243"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41646"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110361"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents with a two-month history of a painless swelling under his jaw (Image). It is slowly increasing in size. He is otherwise in good health and has no other symptoms. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history. His medical history is unremarkable and he is not taking any medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination the swelling is smooth-surfaced, not tender and the skin moves easily over it. No other abnormalities are found.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Submandibular duct calculus","Branchial cyst","Pleomorphic adenoma","Metastatic lymph node deposit","Lipoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis swelling is immediately below the jaw and in the region of the submandibular gland. If the gland was enlarged as the result of a stone in Wharton\u0027s duct, the gland would be expected to change size with the rate of salivary secretion - ie increase in size after a meal. Branchial cysts lie along the anterior border of the sternocleidomastoid. A peri-facial metastatic lymph node may present here from either oral and skin cancer. In the absence of any history of skin cancer or signs of malignancy in the mouth, metastatic cancer is less likely. Lipomas do occasionally occur on the face and neck, but they are usually lobular in shape and not smooth-surfaced. The most likely diagnosis is a \u003Cstrong\u003Epleomorphic\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eadenoma\u003C/strong\u003E of the submandibular salivary gland.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A pleomorphic adenoma is the commonest type of salivary gland tumour."],"references":["Wilson KF, Meier JD, Ward PD. Salivary Gland Disorders. Am Fam Physician 2014; 89:882-88."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92634"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"941"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18431"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18431"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4ed7898e-c9d7-42f8-9267-cf51baad31bc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4ed7898e-c9d7-42f8-9267-cf51baad31bc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":355}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92634",